description.text: The Replicator test print is a handy tool you can use to make sure your Replicator is set up correctly and to diagnose all kinds of print quality issues. Each part of the print diagnoses a different issue: The two rectangles check build platform leveling, the center chip checks nozzle alignment, the squiggle at the right checks gantry alignment, and the two bridges at the front check extruder temperature. Go to http://www.makerbot.com/docs/replicator/calibration-print/ for a more complete explanation of how to use this calibration print.
Combine the two files with the "Merge for Dualstrusion" option in ReplicatorG. Then print the merged files and consult http://www.makerbot.com/docs/replicator/calibration-print/ to check for issues.

description.text:
this is a simple replacement for a window plisse hand grip, which allows to move it up/down.

on the original (transparent) you can change the grip to a different angle. but since it is not needed and makes the printing way more complicated, the replacement is fix.

if it doesn't fit, you have to play around with the scaling.
you can find the original messurements at the pic of the original.

leave me a comment if you had any problems or want the link to the tinkercad project to edit it online.

[update 29.04.17]
i printed the first prototype in PLA. as it seems, it's more important, to use the UV-resistant PLA instead of the heat-resistant ABS.

the strength of the part was greatly increased. but still, i strongly recommend to print with the settings below.

the photos were from v1.0 back then ;-)

Relatively permanent mount on the rear saddle rails for Topeak QuickClick compatible saddle bags.

I made two versions: one flat (original design), & one round so you can slide the whole mount along the rails to find the ideal position.

I also uploaded the bare Base.sldprt in case anyone wants to customize the 2-bolt plate extrusion.

Critical dimensions:

  • Width of big end of the slot: 3.32 mm
  • Width of small end of the slot: 1.78 mm
  • Slot depth: 2.90 mm

Scaled these by 115%.

Counterbored holes for the M5 bolts, only half the original depth of 4 mm, since thickness is critical here, to prevent the pieces from breaking under the compression by the bolts. Used only to help locate the bolts really, but it also lets standard 1/4" 5 mm hex bits reach it without hitting the rail body first.

I decided not to add the locating stub on the original part (almost impossible to see in the image below - it's between the two bolts), since the idea is that you print a bunch of these & leave them on your bike(s). So you can suffer the slightly-more-cumbersome one-time installation. This saves you from printing more supports.

I am aware there are at least 2 variants of the mount out there - the flat styled one shown immediately below, & the round styled one in the Compatibility section. I only own the flat styled one, so that's the one I used to model the part in SW. I think they are both called QuickClick. I believe I may have the older version, & that they've been replaced by the round style (see further down).

I can't seem to find the flat style on the Topeak website (21 Feb 17) at all.

Source style.

The original hardware included:

  • x2 M5 x 16 mm bolts

You should add:

  • x2 M5 locknuts (7.92 mm defining inscribed circle)

You may need longer bolts depending on your saddle rail diameter. I would go longer regardless.

Print either the FLAT pieces or the ROUND pieces. You'll need the base & the plate. The locknuts set inside the plate. Wide wing tips go up.
Your clip (on the bag) should look like this. I am not positive, but I think bags with this style of mount will also work.
• angled variations; I've had problems especially with my saddles too far forward such that the bags need to make a large bend to fit the angle between the rails & the seatpost

24 Feb 17: Just mounted one. Almost everything was perfect the first time. The slot was perfect, but the wall thickness where the clip actually snaps in place was a little too thick. I used a knife to thin it down a little bit. I would also recommend manually pushing the snapping bit (on the bag) up to further secure it even if you hear the click. I printed both pieces so they didn't need any supports. I needed longer-than-16 mm bolts. Exacerbated by the orientation, there was enough warping that one of the hex insets was too big. I wrapped the locknut in electrical tape & wound the bolt through until it was set in the plate. Tightened fairly tight, with no issue.

This is a version of the Sputnik 17 speaker using thinner plywood and larger (4 inch) speakers. What we said of the first version still stands:
Dodecahedron loudspeakers radiate sound in all directions. They also look really cool. This project uses a parametric program that allows anyone to create a dodecahedron loudspeaker using any size speaker.

This is a revision to our original Sputnik 17 speaker. In this version we used thinner plywood (the laser had issues with 6 mm so we switched to 3 mm.), and we found some better, larger speakers (4 inch). We also experimented with an alternative method of mounting the cabinet - in this version we hung the speaker from the ceiling using a large eye-bolt. Very stable, and keeps the workbench clear!
Eli revised his python program that generates the geometry for the speaker. That is included on this page as well. If you want to make a custom size cabinet using different size speakers, just fill in the blanks and use the program to generate your own variant. Easy as Pi!
The instructions for the first version still apply, with the exception of the refinements listed above. (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:17672) Enjoy!

description.text:
This Mystery Presidential Artifact Page is to model for my students how to organize their own "Mystery Presidential Artifact". Students will be posting their own Presidential "Things" in celebration of Presidents' Day.

Students will provide:

  • 3D file of their artifact
  • Screen shot of their Tinkercad file/ the printed object
  • A set of 3-5 clues for other students to guess the president & the significant event
    *Significance & Research w/ Citations
  • Visual Evidence
  • Additional links to find out more about this object, or this President

Read the Clues to Figure Out Which President this Mystery Artifact Represents

Clues...
This object represents a famous Philippine president.
The hand symbol represents a political coalition popularized during the 1980s
This president was the "first" at something.

Can you tell...
Which Philippine president is represented here?
What political movement was the Philippine president part of? How does the hand symbol represent this movement?
Why was this important to Philippine history?

The Object:
*Symbolic: Philippine Map with "Laban" hand sign.

Details about the Object:
The hand is making an "L" hand symbol. President Corazon Aquino often used this hand sign to represent "Laban", a tagalog word for "fight". This was often used during the EDSA Revolution of 1986, the "People's Revolution", which can also be said in Tagalog as "Lakas ng Bayan", abbreviated as "Laban" (Laban, January 2016).

President:
Corazon Aquino
served 1986-1992

Contribution: (Who, What, Where, When, Why):
Chief Executive/ Chief Legislator
Proclaimed a Provisional Constitution to return power to a republic form of government.

President Corazon Aquino was elected president, replacing dicator president Ferdinanad Marcos who had ruled for twenty years and had instituted martial law from 1972- 1981.
President Aquino ended the constitution under President Marcos which had eliminated the Congress, she instituted a Provisional Constitution until a new Congress could be elected to create a new Constitution with proper checks and balances.

Impact on the Philippines:
"I choose this object because it represents this very important act by the President"
As one of her first acts as President, Aquino brought the power of the government back to the people, via an elected legislature. This ended the dictatorial rule set in place by President Ferdinand Ramos.

title: A Step-based Design of a Pencil Holder

description.text: This is just a random sketch I came up with while I was bored in study hall at school. I still do not have a 3D printer so I can not test these out as a practical 3D print. I am just modeling for now and preparing to get enough money to buy a $200 XYZPrinting Da Vinci Junior 1.0 seeing as I am now in the process of getting my first job. Please check out on how I built this model below. If you would like to, please go ahead and download this STL and let me know if printing this was successful! Thank you for reading and go check out some of my other models on my profile.

The Building Process of the "Stepped Pencil Holder"

First, I went into Adobe Illustrator and created a 3" square. I then copied and placed the copied square in front. Then I double-clicked the rotate tool and turned it by 10 degrees. I then proceeded to repeat those steps until i got a complete "circle" in the middle of the multiple squares. I saved it as an SVG file and imported it into a new drawing in 123D Design. From there, I extruded each side up, starting from the top being 4.5" and slowly shortening each by .5". After that, I made a smaller square (2.75" x 2.75") on the top and the bottom. the top square got extruded -3.75", while the bottom square got extruded .5" giving my a gap in the middle for the pencils and a hole in the bottom to keep it light weight and to save on plastic if it was printed. Lastly, I added some fillets and chamfers until I was happy with the model. If you are a beginner at 3D modeling and this helps you learn a bit more about it you can ask me more questions if you would like.

This is a set of coasters based on the turtle select screen from Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles II on the NES. Made for laser cutting. Source image added for reference.

Object made for laser cutting. Designed for material that is 1/8" thick. I used MDF board and colored the pieces with colored pencil (Prismacolor) and black permanent ink. The coasters were then coated with spray on clear enamel as a protective layer to waterproof it. If you want add a soft fabric to the bottom of each coaster, there is enough height to the box to allow for ~1 mm thick piece of fabric. If you decide to use ink to color yours and then coat with spray enamel, you have to do a few light layers of enamel before adding a heavier application--otherwise the spray enamel will dissolve the ink and make it bleed. With MDF the enamel tends to absorb into the wood a little so after about 3 or 4 lightly applied layers, the surface should be sealed of enough to add heavier applications for a glossier finish. This is kinda optional but before applying the enamel I put a couple layers of workable fixatif on the coasters to help protect the ink and also to seal off the wood surface a bit so the enamel wouldn't absorb in as much (the clear enamel will darken the MDF wood a bit, but the fixatif does not).

description.text: This was my very first creation on 123D Design. I was just testing what I could do on the software such as extruding, subtracting, fillets, chamfers, etc. I recommend this software to anyone that is starting to get into 3D modeling and wants to try and learn more about it. This is a very basic and simple design that anyone can make. I just wanted to post this model because I wanted to show that with free software like this, you can really get a good understanding about what 3D modeling is and if this is something you can get really into. I have already made 2 other different models in about 1 day. I still currently do not have a printer, but if you do, please try and print one of my designs and let me know if it is well built or if I should make any adjustments. I am very open minded and am willing to learn from my mistakes. thank you for reading and go check out some of my other 3D models that i have posted on my profile.

The Designing Process of the "Basic Pencil Holder"

At this time, I did not know that I could make an SVG file in Adobe Illustrator and import it to 123D Design. So given this, i just went into the 3D modeling software and created a simple circle sketch and extruded it 5" up. I then made a circle on top of the newly made cylinder about 4.5" in diameter. I took this circle and extruded it down 3.5". I copied the circle onto the bottom of the cylinder and extruded it up .5". I finalized my first ever 3D model by putting fillets on the inside and outside of the top rim and then also putting a chamfer on the inside of the bottom gap I created. Again, a very basic design for my first go at 3D modeling on 123D Design with only a little bit of knowledge in CAD.

Top Isometric View Bottom Isometric View

Without the other three bearings you have to print dense to make up for the loss of weight and it still works great. I wondered what 2 magnets would do if added to the bottom of the begleri beads. I have yet to figure out if there are some new tricks one could do with this, but it stores away nicely, even wrapped around the fingers....

with my printer, after some cleanup, the magnets and the caps are a rather tight press fit using a vice... it worked the first try with the file i uploaded without cracking. The magnets I used are cylindric, 4mm x 4mm.
I imported the original STL in tinkercad, flattened the bottom and designed a cap to house the magnets.

description.text:
OpenForge 2.0 OpenLock 4
As requested, a set of magnetic based OpenForge 2.0 design (OpenLock compatable) roleplaying terrain features/accessories to depict a spiral staircase as in a corner tower. Modified all three styles of stairs to accept any of the OpenForge 2.0 /OpenLock 4 6mm thick plain bases.
Included, is a cut stone OpenLock magnetic combination base with the bottom tread. This is optional as the bottom tread blocks one of the four OpenLock clip keyholes in an E style tile. If you want to skip using the tread, just download an open base here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1910969 or the standard plain base here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1833963

Cut trimmed base tread is also included, as is the blender file with the tread and cut stone mag base layout, for those that would want to substitute another style open base with the tread.

v2 is revised to remove the small hole, and rotate to correctly view the models.

Modified xloud's spiral staircase (up and down) for OpenForge to the OpenForge 2.0/OpenLock 4.0 standards. Use Devon Jones Openforge Floors and OpenForge Curved Walls to mesh together. Resized to 25.4x50.8x50.8.

Note! have not printed to verify compatibility as of 02/24/17. The 2 models with the down level would be useful to utilize the lighting effect in: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2125958
